        <h3>My Role</h3>
        <p>I used my UX skill set to manage and execute this project at a fast pace. I drafted and wrote content, created user scenarios, prototypes, and content tracking documents. Finally, I designed, coded, launched and managed the web site and content marketing moving forward.</p>
     
        
        <h3>Problem</h3>
        <p>Healthentic had a good customer base, but its sales and go-to-market strategy was not performing up to expectations. After working at Healthentic for three years, I was in for the wild ride of a company acceleration effort. My product, design, and communications background meant I would be on point for defining the value for customers and potential customers.</p>

        <p>The leadership team wanted to put a data-driven sales pipeline in place that used the web as a key cornerstone for lead generation. I had about three weeks to create new product messaging and design and build a web site to support it. Continued iteration was a given, so whatever the approach, I needed to make sure I could continue to make fast, incremental changes post launch. One important business requirement was that the site had to provide metrics on our site traffic and landing pages, so the architecture needed to support this by design.</p>


